<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,649,1324]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,649,675]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name is a combination of the prefix “ 
<emphasis box="[853,917,650,675]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">micro</emphasis>
” (Greek, means “small/little”) and the second part of the genus name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1804" box="[414,547,685,711]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Heteropoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[414,547,685,711]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Heteropoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It was chosen in reference to the small body size of the only known species of the new genus. The gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,649,1324]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,757,783]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bertkau" authorityYear="1872" box="[407,539,757,783]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sparassidae</taxonomicName>
with TL &lt;7.0 (
<figureCitation box="[730,865,757,783]" captionStart="FIGURES 82–97" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1899,1923]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,182,1873]" captionTargetId="figure-19@19.[151,1436,181,1875]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 82–97. Heteropodinae gen. &amp; spp. nov., habitus (dorsal and ventral, respectively). 82–85 Borniella parva gen. &amp; spec. nov.; 86–89 Menarik kecil gen. &amp; spec. nov.; 90–93 Micropoda davisae gen. &amp; spec. nov.; 94–97 Tiomaniella ladam gen. &amp; spec. nov. (82–83, 86–87, 90–91, 94–95 holotype male, 84–85, 88–89, 92–93, 96–97 female paratype)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911203/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs 90–93</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Grall &amp; Jäger, 2022" authorityName="Grall &amp; Jäger" authorityYear="2022" box="[886,1009,757,783]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Micropoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[886,1009,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Micropoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1020,1128,757,783]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1020,1128,757,783]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
may be recognised by the following combination of characters: Males (
<figureCitation box="[661,795,793,820]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–52" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[167,1407,203,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-21@12.[167,1420,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 47–52. Micropoda daviesae gen. &amp; spec. nov. holotype male from New Britain. 47–49 Right palp, mirrored (47 prolateral, 48 ventral, 49 retrolateral); 50 Proximal part of cymbium and tegulum showing embolus base and alveolus pocket; 51 RTA, ventro-distal; 52 Tip of embolus and embolic apophysis, retrolateral. AP—alveolus pocket, bT—big tooth at RTA, C—conductor, dlA—dorso-lateral apex of RTA, E—embolus, EA—embolic apophysis, RTA—retrolateral tibial apophysis, S—spermophor, sT—small tooth at RTA, ST—subtegulum, TR—tegular ridge, vlA—ventro-lateral apex of RTA." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911181" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911181/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs 47–52</figureCitation>
): 1. Tegulum with a narrow, but distinct ridge, running a semi-circle from proximal to distal, 2. Alveolus proximally with indistinct pocket in which embolus base is partly hidden, 3. Conductor (homologue) reduced to indistinct bulge at distal tegulum and 4. Embolus with apophysis. Other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thorell" authorityYear="1873" box="[221,386,901,927]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heteropodinae">Heteropodinae</taxonomicName>
with an embolic apophysis, such as most 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jager" authorityYear="1999" box="[851,957,901,927]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Sinopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[851,957,901,927]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Sinopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, few 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1804" box="[1019,1152,901,927]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Heteropoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1019,1152,901,927]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Heteropoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or all 
<taxonomicName box="[1222,1382,901,927]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis box="[1222,1295,901,927]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Yiinthi</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
(sub “flagellum”: 
<bibRefCitation author="Davies, V. T." box="[299,442,937,963]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="75 - 122" refId="ref11957" refString="Davies, V. T. (1994) The huntsman spiders Heteropoda Latreille and Yiinthi gen. nov. (Araneae: Heteropodidae) in Australia. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 35, 75 - 122." type="journal article" year="1994">Davies 1994</bibRefCitation>
) possess a well-developed conductor and lack the alveolus pocket as well as the tegular ridge. Females (
<figureCitation box="[329,460,973,1000]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–57" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1742,1766]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,561,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-220@13.[151,1436,561,1718]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 53–57. Micropoda daviesae gen. &amp; spec. nov. female paratype from New Britain, copulatory organ. 53 Epigyne, ventral; 54, 56 Vulva (54 dorsal, 56 lateral); 55, 57 Schematic course of internal duct system (55 dorsal, 57 lateral). EF—epigynal field, EP—epigynal pocket, FD—fertilization ducts, FW—first winding of internal duct system, GA—glandular appendages, LL—lateral lobes, SP—spermatheca, Wi—window of first winding." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911187" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911187/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Figs 53–57</figureCitation>
): 1. First winding dorsad, both sides fused, running a distinct semi-circle, leaving a window between outer cuticle and internal duct, 2. Lateral lobes ear-shaped and with narrow and long epigynal pockets, situated laterally and 3. Internal duct system with only short glandular appendages anteriorly (but functionally after the first winding) and distinctly convoluted ducts in the posterior part. Few 
<taxonomicName box="[993,1152,1081,1108]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Sinopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[993,1099,1081,1107]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Sinopoda</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
exhibit a similar window between outer cuticle and duct system (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Jager &amp; Ono, 2002" authorityName="Jager &amp; Ono" authorityYear="2002" box="[643,980,1117,1144]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Sinopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="derivata">
<emphasis box="[643,763,1117,1144]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">S. derivata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Jager, P. &amp; Ono, H." box="[770,980,1117,1144]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="109 - 124" refId="ref12915" refString="Jager, P. &amp; Ono, H. (2002) The Sparassidae from Japan. II. First Pseudopoda species and new Sinopoda species (Araneae: Sparassidae: Heteropodinae). Acta Arachnologica, 51, 109 - 124. https: // doi. org / 10.2476 / asjaa. 51.109" type="journal article" year="2002">Jäger &amp; Ono, 2002</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authority="Jager &amp; Ono, 2002" authorityName="Jager &amp; Ono" authorityYear="2002" box="[1016,1335,1117,1144]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Sinopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ogatai">
<emphasis box="[1016,1115,1118,1144]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">S. ogatai</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Jager, P. &amp; Ono, H." box="[1121,1335,1117,1144]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="109 - 124" refId="ref12915" refString="Jager, P. &amp; Ono, H. (2002) The Sparassidae from Japan. II. First Pseudopoda species and new Sinopoda species (Araneae: Sparassidae: Heteropodinae). Acta Arachnologica, 51, 109 - 124. https: // doi. org / 10.2476 / asjaa. 51.109" type="journal article" year="2002">Jäger &amp; Ono, 2002</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
), but it is formed by the part functionally behind the glandular appendages. Moreover, epigynal pockets in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jager" authorityYear="1999" box="[1222,1328,1153,1179]" class="Arachnida" family="Sparassidae" genus="Sinopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1222,1328,1153,1179]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Sinopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are never exclusively situated laterally, and the internal duct system is much simpler and shows no coils.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,705,1225,1252]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,649,1324]" box="[199,705,1225,1252]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
